<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-09-27T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-09-27T15:00:00-05:00" n="348" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d348">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15 Arms Truce/49: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-27T15:00:00-05:00">September 27, 1931—3
                                    p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>129. Your 167 September 26, 6 [<hi rend="italic">8</hi>] p.m. and 168
                            September 27, 11 a.m. In the hope of seeing a text which embodies the
                            spirit of an armaments <pb facs="0576" n="462" xml:id="pg_462"/> holiday
                            unanimously adopted, we are prepared to acquiesce in the French version.
                            You may so inform the Third Committee and add that well before November
                            1st this Government hopes to be able to make the declaration called for,
                            subject of course to similar action on the part of the principal
                            Military and Naval Powers.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>